### Issue details

On the java/class input path, `new long[n][]` decompiles to `new long[n]` (the outer dimension is dropped) and the method gets a spurious `Type inference failed` warning.
This happens for any `anewarray` whose element type is itself an array.

`InsnDecoder.makeNewArray` ([InsnDecoder.java:529](https://github.com/skylot/jadx/blob/8c28a8530e0fb2d2caba930b38f0f936f118d490/jadx-core/src/main/java/jadx/core/dex/instructions/InsnDecoder.java#L529)) cannot tell java `anewarray` (operand is the element type, e.g. `[J` for `new long[n][]`, with dim literal 1) from `multianewarray` (operand is the full result type); both arrive as `Opcode.NEW_ARRAY`.
The `if (indexType.isArray())` shortcut ([InsnDecoder.java:536](https://github.com/skylot/jadx/blob/8c28a8530e0fb2d2caba930b38f0f936f118d490/jadx-core/src/main/java/jadx/core/dex/instructions/InsnDecoder.java#L536), added in 7576f9cd) treats any array operand as already the full type, so `anewarray` of an array element keeps only the element type and loses the outer dimension.
The dex path is unaffected (dalvik `new-array` carries the full type with dim 0).
`multianewarray` (e.g. `new int[a][b]`) is correct and must stay correct.

### Sample

Compile with `javac` and run jadx on the `.class`:

```java
public class ArrBug {
    public static long[][] makeLong(int n) { return new long[n][]; }
    public static String[][] makeStr(int n) { return new String[n][]; }
    public static int[][][] makeDeep(int n) { return new int[n][][]; }
    public static int[][] makeMulti(int a, int b) { return new int[a][b]; }
}
```

Current output on master (8c28a85):

```java
public static long[][] makeLong(int i) {
    return new long[i];      // expected: new long[i][]
}
public static String[][] makeStr(int i) {
    return new String[i];    // expected: new String[i][]
}
public static int[][][] makeDeep(int i) {
    return new int[i][];     // expected: new int[i][][]
}
public static int[][] makeMulti(int i, int i2) {
    return new int[i][i2];   // correct (multianewarray)
}
```

Each broken method also gets a `JADX WARN: Type inference failed ...` comment.

